1
00:00:06,370 --> 00:00:09,570
Lionel Andres Messi

2
00:00:09,570 --> 00:00:21,030
Hailed by football enthusiasts, analysts, and even fellow professionals as the greatest footballer to ever play the sport.

3
00:00:21,030 --> 00:00:30,750
<i>【Spanish】There are people who tell me, I saw Pelé play, I saw Maradona play, I can say that I saw Leo Messi play.</i>

4
00:00:30,750 --> 00:00:40,369
He doesn't have the ball. It's unbelievable the character, how he plays, how he works for the team. He's one of the gods of football.

5
00:00:40,369 --> 00:00:53,490
He has achieved a groundbreaking six Ballon d'Or awards, six European Golden Shoes, and holds records for the most goals and assists in La Liga history.

6
00:00:53,490 --> 00:01:01,929
【Spanish】It's an award for the group, more than individually, because there are a lot of goals and I just didn't get it.

7
00:01:01,929 --> 00:01:13,109
Diagnosed with a medical condition at just 11 years old that could have derailed his career before it even started, Messi defied expectations and stunned the world with his extraordinary footballing talent.

8
00:01:13,109 --> 00:01:17,049
Statistics and history go out the window, the way he's playing.

9
00:01:17,049 --> 00:01:26,030
Experience the journey of one of football's most legendary figures, and delve into the story of Argentina's footballing icon.

10
00:01:26,030 --> 00:01:33,590
【Spanish】I grew up, I learned a lot, and now I try to keep adding things to my football.

11
00:01:33,590 --> 00:01:49,760
This is the mesmerizing tale of Lionel Messi.

12
00:01:49,760 --> 00:01:58,719
【Spanish】I've always said that I don't play to be the best in history, or the best of the moment, or anything like that.

13
00:01:58,719 --> 00:02:11,039
【Spanish】I play to try to do things right, first for the team, whether it's Barcelona or the Argentine national team, then for the people and, above all, for me.

14
00:02:11,039 --> 00:02:24,550
Born on June 24, 1987, Lionel Andres Messi grew up in a city that breathes football, Rosario, the largest city in Santa Fe.

15
00:02:24,550 --> 00:02:36,199
Messi was raised by his father, a steel factory manager and part-time football coach, and his mother, who worked in a magnet manufacturing workshop.

16
00:02:36,199 --> 00:02:43,759
His family shared an immense passion for football, spending weekends watching matches and engaging in the sport whenever possible.

17
00:02:43,759 --> 00:02:50,139
Well, Messi was born into a football family. His dad was a coach, and he was born in a football city.

18
00:02:50,139 --> 00:02:58,039
Rosario in Argentina was one of the host cities for the World Cup in 1978, almost ten years before Messi was born.

19
00:02:58,039 --> 00:03:04,620
This is a city that loves the game, and it's a family that loves the game, that is steeped in the game through his father.

20
00:03:04,620 --> 00:03:18,259
And Lionel Messi, his first influence is through, of course, his father's love for football, but also his grandmother's willingness to take him anywhere that football takes him as he begins to make his way in the local football scene.

21
00:03:18,259 --> 00:03:22,280
Messi quickly developed a passion for the sport as he was surrounded by it.

22
00:03:22,280 --> 00:03:31,759
He constantly played with his older brothers, Rodrigo and Matias, and by the age of four was determined to join a local team.

23
00:03:31,759 --> 00:03:43,860
His father, who is a coach, takes him to the local club, Grandoli, and looks after him there, and influences his first steps as a very young player, four years old when he goes to Grandoli.

24
00:03:43,860 --> 00:03:50,960
But of course, Newell's old boys are the Rosario club, and the club that Messi has supported all his life.

25
00:03:50,960 --> 00:04:00,539
And, you know, very quickly they become aware of any emerging talent on their doorstep, and little Lionel Messi is very much an emerging talent.

26
00:04:00,539 --> 00:04:07,800
Messi moved clubs when he was six years old, joining the Newell's old boys, a local club located in Rosario.

27
00:04:07,800 --> 00:04:17,600
Here he played for over six years, developed his skills even more, garnering more match experience, and surrounded himself with other future prospect players.

28
00:04:17,600 --> 00:04:24,019
Whilst at Newell's, Messi was already showing off what type of player he was going to become in the six years at the club.

29
00:04:24,019 --> 00:04:39,019
He went on to score almost 500 goals, and became a member of the Machine of 87, who were named that due to the fact that they were the near unbeatable youth side since their birth in 1987.

30
00:04:39,019 --> 00:04:55,720
Audiences loved watching Messi play, as he was not only scoring regularly, he would also perform tricks at halftime.

31
00:04:55,720 --> 00:05:25,720
【Spanish】It seemed like his career in football was going to blossom. But at the age of 11, Messi received some news that would put his professional football career at risk.

32
00:05:25,720 --> 00:05:37,139
The problem for Lionel Messi is that it becomes apparent by the age of 11 that he's not really growing at all, and he's diagnosed with this growth hormone deficiency, which casts his whole future into doubt.

33
00:05:37,139 --> 00:05:45,819
【Spanish】He was aware that he was young, and that he was at a disadvantage in sports.

34
00:05:45,819 --> 00:05:59,060
【Spanish】When kids don't grow up, they're interested in being tall, because they want to be taller, because of their looks, because of the girls, because he wanted to play football.

35
00:05:59,060 --> 00:06:03,379
【Spanish】He always said that he was going to grow up to play football, because he wanted to play.

36
00:06:03,379 --> 00:06:12,790
【Spanish】And I told him, don't worry, you're going to be taller than Maradona. I don't know if you're going to be better, but you're going to be taller.

37
00:06:12,790 --> 00:06:19,370
Messi underwent the treatment despite the fact that it cost his family almost $1,000 a month.

38
00:06:19,370 --> 00:06:26,769
He continued to play for Newell's, putting in great performances every week. But things were about to change for the young Lionel Messi.

39
00:06:26,769 --> 00:06:37,149
So Messi at this stage is still with Newell's, he's still trying to tackle this problem of will he grow enough to be a footballer. Some people say he's never going to amount to anything.

40
00:06:37,149 --> 00:06:52,290
River Plate are interested in signing him as well. But the family looked beyond that. He has connections in Spain, in Catalonia, and he ends up at the age of 13 having a trial with Barcelona, and Barcelona immediately want to sign him.

41
00:06:52,290 --> 00:06:57,910
The Messi family travelled to Barcelona after receiving the go-ahead for the trial.

42
00:06:57,910 --> 00:07:06,410
Almost immediately during the trial, Barcelona's first team director, Carles Rexach, wanted to sign him as he saw an instant talent.

43
00:07:06,410 --> 00:07:13,189
But unfortunately, due to his age and the fact he wasn't from Catalonia, the board of directors were hesitant to bring him in.

44
00:07:13,189 --> 00:07:23,649
If you try and imagine the 13-year-olds at a trial with Barcelona, these are not the ordinary kids that you and I play with on the street. These are already the creme de la creme.

45
00:07:23,649 --> 00:07:36,449
But when Lionel Messi walks into this trial, nobody at Barcelona is under any illusions at all. He is the cream of that already very, very exclusive club, and they have to have him.

46
00:07:36,449 --> 00:07:49,870
A few months later, Barcelona were given the final chance to sign the Argentine prodigy, and on the 14th of December, Messi was offered his contract, which was written on a paper napkin.

47
00:07:49,870 --> 00:08:05,319
Barcelona was his new home, and in February 2001, the Messi family relocated to an apartment in the city.

48
00:08:05,319 --> 00:08:14,319
Despite being signed to one of the biggest clubs in Europe, Messi was finding it hard to integrate into the youth squad due to the Spanish footballing law.

49
00:08:14,319 --> 00:08:25,980
He was unable to play any games apart from friendlies and Catalan league games. Because of this, his relationship with other teammates was almost non-existent, with some of them labeling him a meat.

50
00:08:25,980 --> 00:08:36,820
On top of that, his mother moved back to Rosario with his brothers and little sister, leaving him with just his father, causing him to feel constantly homesick.

51
00:08:36,820 --> 00:08:45,679
Eventually, in 2002, Messi was enrolled in the Royal Spanish Football Federation, meaning he was now eligible to play in all competitions.

52
00:08:45,679 --> 00:08:53,139
He had also befriended some of his junior teammates. Those included Cesc Fabregas and Gerard Pique.

53
00:08:53,139 --> 00:09:08,320
Now eligible to play in all competitions, Messi displayed his true talent to all the Barcelona staff, and that year Messi became part of the youth team known as the Baby Dream Team, Barcelona's greatest ever youth side.

54
00:09:08,320 --> 00:09:20,500
During his first season in 2002-2003, Messi ended up the top scorer with 36 goals in just 30 games because of this phenomenal season for the Cadets.

55
00:09:20,500 --> 00:09:34,539
Messi was getting recognized all over Europe in 2003. He received an offer from Arsenal to join the team. But despite the fantastic offer, Messi decided he wanted to stay loyal to Barcelona.

56
00:09:34,539 --> 00:09:46,879
The 2003-2004 season became an iconic season for Lionel Messi. Within this season, he flew up the ranks, debuting for a record five teams in a single campaign.

57
00:09:46,879 --> 00:09:55,480
During this season, he played for the Juveniles B, Juveniles A, Barcelona C, and Barcelona B teams.

58
00:09:55,480 --> 00:10:09,399
Before he'd even got into Barcelona's first team, all the first-teamers were aware of him. There'd been this occasion where a lot of them were away on an international break, and so they needed players to come in and take part in first-team training, and Messi was one of those.

59
00:10:09,399 --> 00:10:19,220
And Ludovic Juli, the Barcelona French international player who was part of this training session, tells this story about how this little kid was absolutely destroying people.

60
00:10:19,220 --> 00:10:29,220
And grown men were being embarrassed by this little 15, 16-year-old kid on the training pitch, and Frank Rijkaard could not ignore him.

61
00:10:29,220 --> 00:10:39,279
And very, very quickly, the Barcelona first-team was saying, this boy has to be involved.

62
00:10:39,279 --> 00:10:58,580
And at that time, Ronaldinho was the man at Barcelona, and Ronaldinho saw Lionel Messi train, and he picked him out as being the next Ronaldinho, the next big thing for Barcelona, and was insisting, more or less, that Lionel Messi became part of the first-team scene at the club.

63
00:10:58,580 --> 00:11:11,960
Although Messi didn't officially play for the team in this season, he did finish that campaign, having scored for four of his five teams with a total of 36 goals in all official competition.

64
00:11:11,960 --> 00:11:22,580
Going into the 2004-2005 season, Messi finally made his debut for the Barcelona first-team, coming onto the field in the 82nd minute.

65
00:11:22,580 --> 00:11:35,559
So when he was 17 and three months old, Lionel Messi became the youngest ever player to play in Barcelona's first team, coming on as a substitute against Espanyol, and his first goal followed soon after.

66
00:11:35,559 --> 00:11:54,269
Also the youngest player ever to score a goal for Barcelona's first team against Alba Fete at the end of that season, which finished in 2005.

67
00:11:54,269 --> 00:12:00,789
So now Lionel Messi, at the insistence of his teammates, is in the Barcelona side.

68
00:12:00,789 --> 00:12:05,730
Messi clocked over 77 minutes in just nine matches for the Barcelona team during this season.

69
00:12:05,730 --> 00:12:10,230
He was also a regular player for the B team, and a key one as well.

70
00:12:10,230 --> 00:12:26,610
But by the end of the season, it was clear to both staff and fans that Messi was the next superstar in the making, and was going to become a key player in the 2005-2006 season and the 2005-2006 campaign.

71
00:12:26,610 --> 00:12:33,830
Lionel Messi was a full-time first-team player. He had been fully promoted from the B team, and was training with the team on a daily basis.

72
00:12:33,830 --> 00:12:39,629
Within the first few games, Messi was blowing away fans on both sides of the stadiums.

73
00:12:39,629 --> 00:12:44,269
His skills were truly on show, and his abilities were becoming renowned everywhere he went.

74
00:12:44,269 --> 00:12:54,309
While still a teenager, the world is taking note of Messi and recognizing that he is one of the greatest players already in the game at this very tender age.

75
00:12:54,309 --> 00:13:04,370
What he has, I think, is this incredible low center of gravity, such acceleration, such tremendous pace, he can glide across the ground.

76
00:13:04,370 --> 00:13:11,230
But he's also got an incredible physical strength, which despite his size, you wouldn't imagine that he could be as strong as he is.

77
00:13:11,230 --> 00:13:16,669
But he is literally kicked from pillar to post game in, game out, and it doesn't seem to affect him.

78
00:13:16,669 --> 00:13:25,990
He just gets back onto his feet and dribbles around people again, and it never seems to knock him.

79
00:13:25,990 --> 00:13:30,590
Here's the youngest. Oh, look at that! Poetic for Messi.

80
00:13:30,590 --> 00:13:40,730
And it's that kind of persistence and incredible strength to go with the pace and skill, which signals him out at this age as being something really, really special.

81
00:13:40,730 --> 00:13:45,129
Messi was starring in some of the biggest games Barcelona played in this season.

82
00:13:45,129 --> 00:13:52,389
He played four games against the biggest rivals, Real Madrid in La Liga, and Chelsea in the semi-final of the Champions League.

83
00:13:52,389 --> 00:14:02,309
Together with players like Samuel Eto'o and Ronaldinho, Messi was easily becoming a key player for Barcelona and helped strengthen their attacking force.

84
00:14:02,309 --> 00:14:10,450
But unfortunately, near the end of the season, Messi suffered from a hamstring injury, which would put him out of the first team completely,

85
00:14:10,450 --> 00:14:14,850
meaning he would go on to miss the Champions League final against Arsenal in Paris.

86
00:14:14,850 --> 00:14:26,980
Messi was devastated by this so much that he didn't even celebrate their win, something that he later came to regret.

87
00:14:26,980 --> 00:14:36,039
After fully recovering going into the 2006-2007 season, Barcelona were gradually declining in La Liga and European tournaments.

88
00:14:36,039 --> 00:14:40,940
But this didn't stop Messi's performance and actually helped him to develop more as a player.

89
00:14:40,940 --> 00:14:47,080
And despite the poor Barcelona form, this was actually Messi's most groundbreaking season so far.

90
00:14:47,080 --> 00:14:53,480
During this season, he went on to score 17 goals in just 36 games across all competitions.

91
00:14:53,480 --> 00:15:00,620
He also got his first hat-trick for the club, scoring against their closest rivals, Real Madrid, in the Clásico match.

92
00:15:00,620 --> 00:15:22,889
This hat-trick meant that Messi was the first person to score one in an El Clásico match in over 12 years.

93
00:15:22,889 --> 00:15:27,950
This is the game that is going to be remembered as the Lionel Messi match.

94
00:15:27,950 --> 00:15:32,190
It was clear that Messi was becoming an extremely important asset for the club

95
00:15:32,190 --> 00:15:38,570
and was actually being compared to his fellow countryman and footballing legend, Diego Maradona.

96
00:15:38,570 --> 00:15:47,389
This comparison was made clear to fans in April 2007, when Messi went on to score what could only be described as a Maradona-esque goal

97
00:15:47,389 --> 00:15:51,750
against Getafe in the first leg of the Copa del Rey semi-finals.

98
00:15:51,750 --> 00:16:00,309
There probably isn't a football fan in the world that hasn't seen the Diego Maradona goal against England in the World Cup quarter-final of 1986 in Mexico

99
00:16:00,309 --> 00:16:04,570
when he runs from inside his own half of the field, pretty much through the whole England team

100
00:16:04,570 --> 00:16:22,090
and glides around Peter Shilton and tucks the ball into the back of the net.

101
00:16:22,090 --> 00:16:28,850
Absolutely certain that there's no Argentine who hasn't seen that goal a countless number of times

102
00:16:28,850 --> 00:16:33,230
and of course Lionel Messi would have grown up with that goal from the great Maradona.

103
00:16:33,230 --> 00:16:39,929
So then in the Copa del Rey against Getafe, Messi picks the ball up inside his own half of the field.

104
00:16:39,929 --> 00:16:47,429
I wonder at what point he realises that he's almost scoring the exact same goal, because it is extraordinary.

105
00:16:47,429 --> 00:16:53,889
From almost the same area of the pitch, beating players in exactly the same way, finishing in virtually the same way,

106
00:16:53,889 --> 00:16:59,970
Lionel Messi replicates one of the greatest goals we've ever seen.

107
00:16:59,970 --> 00:17:04,868
Oh, brilliant skill from Lionel Messi.

108
00:17:04,868 --> 00:17:11,430
Surging forward with real menace here. Brilliant from Messi. Oh, what a goal that is!

109
00:17:11,430 --> 00:17:16,509
This goal sent shockwaves all over the world as it was not only a good goal,

110
00:17:16,509 --> 00:17:24,519
it was a world-class goal that could only be achieved by a few people.

111
00:17:24,519 --> 00:17:29,420
Messi was being regarded as the best player in the world and still at only the age of 19.

112
00:17:29,420 --> 00:17:36,660
With Ronaldinho out of the squad and the following season, he had become the star player for the squad.

113
00:17:36,660 --> 00:17:43,440
At the 2007 Ballon d'Or, Messi made the podium alongside Kaka and Cristiano Ronaldo.

114
00:17:43,440 --> 00:17:48,880
He unfortunately finished in the third spot, but it was still an incredible achievement for him.

115
00:17:48,880 --> 00:17:56,700
He also got nominated for FIFA World Player of the Year, coming second again behind Kaka, but beating Cristiano Ronaldo.

116
00:17:56,700 --> 00:18:01,680
He had finally had a taste of what it was like to be an award-winning player,

117
00:18:01,680 --> 00:18:09,720
but his mission to become the best player ever was still not over.

118
00:18:09,720 --> 00:18:15,500
Going into 2008, Barcelona were failing to achieve any form of success.

119
00:18:15,500 --> 00:18:22,019
The past two seasons had seen them trophy-less and not even contenders for top position in La Liga.

120
00:18:22,019 --> 00:18:28,680
Ronaldinho had dramatically lost all form and was not even considered one of the best players in the world anymore.

121
00:18:28,680 --> 00:18:35,579
And on top of that regard, the Barcelona manager, who had previously led Barcelona to win the league two times in a row,

122
00:18:35,579 --> 00:18:37,599
had lost control of his team.

123
00:18:37,599 --> 00:18:43,539
Things needed to change and in 2009, Barcelona were appointed with their new manager,

124
00:18:43,539 --> 00:18:46,740
the former Barcelona captain Pep Guardiola.

125
00:18:46,740 --> 00:18:52,140
Messi continued at the start of this 2009 season to play on the wing.

126
00:18:52,140 --> 00:18:57,099
During this first season under Guardiola, Messi finally won his first Ballon d'Or

127
00:18:57,099 --> 00:19:05,339
and FIFA World Player of the Year award, winning the awards by their greatest voting margin in each trophy's history.

128
00:19:05,339 --> 00:19:10,380
But going into the 2010 season, Guardiola would go on to change his role,

129
00:19:10,380 --> 00:19:16,900
a decision that would actually make Messi the player that he is known for today.

130
00:19:16,900 --> 00:19:22,359
He changed everything for us, for the club.

131
00:19:22,359 --> 00:19:46,140
They got everything they could and for me, Guardiola is fundamental in this whole Barcelona project.

132
00:19:46,140 --> 00:19:49,019
He was licensed to roam and cut inside.

133
00:19:49,019 --> 00:19:52,839
And when Guardiola took over at Barcelona, that's where Messi started off as well.

134
00:19:52,839 --> 00:19:58,740
But it was Guardiola probably who had the vision to see that maybe that was a position which restricted him

135
00:19:58,740 --> 00:20:04,980
and actually to get Lionel Messi unleashed, he had to move him into the middle.

136
00:20:04,980 --> 00:20:06,160
And that's what he did.

137
00:20:06,160 --> 00:20:13,380
In all matches, in the Clásico against Real Madrid, Messi pops up as a kind of a false nine position

138
00:20:13,380 --> 00:20:20,140
and suddenly we see that Messi is capable of even more than we've seen from him on that right-hand side of midfield.

139
00:20:20,140 --> 00:20:24,859
It's very good from both sides up front, Rob.

140
00:20:24,859 --> 00:20:31,339
This could be a killer goal. Lionel Messi takes his time and walks it in.

141
00:20:31,339 --> 00:20:36,940
Start shining the trophy now. The league may well be Barcelona's.

142
00:20:36,940 --> 00:20:48,720
First of all, it would be very difficult to find another coach to do what he did here.

143
00:20:48,720 --> 00:20:54,240
Everything he won and more than that, how he made the team play.

144
00:20:54,240 --> 00:20:59,019
Because if Barcelona has been playing like this for four years, it's because he did it like this,

145
00:20:59,019 --> 00:21:04,660
because he did it this way, because of how he prepares the training sessions,

146
00:21:04,660 --> 00:21:11,559
how he prepares the matches and how he wants his team to play.

147
00:21:11,559 --> 00:21:18,140
I think the image that Barcelona has given in these four years speaks for itself,

148
00:21:18,140 --> 00:21:24,579
for the game they play, for the recognition they've had all over the world.

149
00:21:24,579 --> 00:21:29,559
I don't think they've had any help from anyone.

150
00:21:29,559 --> 00:21:33,519
For some reason, they've been recognised as the best team in the world.

151
00:21:33,519 --> 00:21:37,099
And a lot of people say they're the best in history.

152
00:21:37,099 --> 00:21:43,079
So I don't think we have to give importance to what they say.

153
00:21:43,079 --> 00:21:47,400
The false nine position became Guardiola's trademark and for mercy.

154
00:21:47,400 --> 00:21:51,200
It's helped him become much more of a threat in front of goal.

155
00:21:51,200 --> 00:21:58,420
During the 2009-2010 season, Messi went on to break the goal-scoring record for Barcelona,

156
00:21:58,420 --> 00:22:06,009
a record that had been set previously by the legendary Barcelona striker Ronaldo in 1996.

157
00:22:06,009 --> 00:22:14,480
So in 2009-10, Messi manages to equal this record of 47 goals scored by the Brazilian Ronaldo,

158
00:22:14,480 --> 00:22:17,519
the man that they called the phenomenon.

159
00:22:17,519 --> 00:22:23,079
And Messi manages to equal that, 47 goals in a season for Barcelona,

160
00:22:23,079 --> 00:22:27,299
a football club which has had as many great strikers as Barcelona have,

161
00:22:27,299 --> 00:22:30,140
and have had Ronaldo, the great Brazilian.

162
00:22:30,140 --> 00:22:32,640
Messi comes along and equals what he's done.

163
00:22:32,640 --> 00:22:34,819
I mean, it is extraordinary to do that.

164
00:22:34,819 --> 00:22:39,859
Season in, season out, Messi begins scoring goals at ridiculous numbers.

165
00:22:39,859 --> 00:22:42,819
Under Pep Guardiola, Barcelona were thriving again.

166
00:22:42,819 --> 00:22:49,640
Messi also went on to win his second Ballon d'Or and FIFA World Player of the Year award.

167
00:22:49,640 --> 00:22:52,579
They went on to win the La Liga title once again,

168
00:22:52,579 --> 00:22:58,359
and in 2011, Messi finished the season with 53 goals and 24 assists,

169
00:22:58,359 --> 00:23:01,579
becoming Barcelona's all-time single-season top scorer

170
00:23:01,579 --> 00:23:06,480
and the first player in Spanish football to reach the 50-goal benchmark.

171
00:23:06,480 --> 00:23:11,519
On top of that, he once again won the Ballon d'Or, making this his third win,

172
00:23:11,519 --> 00:23:17,220
allowing him to become the fourth player in history to win the Ballon d'Or three times.

173
00:23:17,220 --> 00:23:22,380
But going into the next season, his previous groundbreaking record of 53 goals in a season

174
00:23:22,380 --> 00:23:34,180
would seem just like a drop in the ocean compared to his 2012 to 2013 campaign.

175
00:23:34,180 --> 00:23:38,460
Messi's not just a goal scorer, of course, he does so much more than that,

176
00:23:38,460 --> 00:23:44,339
but he was shattering records set by the greatest goal scorers of all time,

177
00:23:44,339 --> 00:23:47,359
guys who did not much more than just score goals,

178
00:23:47,359 --> 00:23:51,940
saw their records fall to a guy who did so much more than just score goals.

179
00:23:51,940 --> 00:23:58,779
In 1972, Gerd Müller had scored 85 goals in that calendar year for Bayern Munich and Germany.

180
00:23:58,779 --> 00:24:04,680
Well, in 2012, Lionel Messi scored 91, breaking that record.

181
00:24:04,680 --> 00:24:08,920
An extraordinary feat, 91 goals in a calendar year,

182
00:24:08,920 --> 00:24:13,720
averaging more than 1.5 goals per game in La Liga.

183
00:24:13,720 --> 00:24:57,720
It's insane.

184
00:24:57,720 --> 00:25:13,819
What I can say about Messi, more than I was talking or the people were talking,

185
00:25:13,819 --> 00:25:16,440
he's one of the gods of football.

186
00:25:16,440 --> 00:25:22,779
It's unbelievable, the design, it's unbelievable, the capacity,

187
00:25:22,779 --> 00:25:30,039
to fight with the ball on the feet, to fight without the ball on the feet.

188
00:25:30,039 --> 00:25:33,079
What happens when he touches the ball?

189
00:25:33,079 --> 00:25:37,680
When he doesn't have the ball, it's unbelievable, the character,

190
00:25:37,680 --> 00:25:42,980
how we press, how we work for the team.

191
00:25:42,980 --> 00:25:48,559
Scoring 91 goals in a single calendar year got acknowledged by the Guinness World Records,

192
00:25:48,559 --> 00:25:52,640
and he continues to hold that record due to this phenomenal season.

193
00:25:52,640 --> 00:25:55,940
Messi also went on to win his fourth Ballon d'Or,

194
00:25:55,940 --> 00:25:59,460
becoming the first player to ever win four trophies.

195
00:25:59,460 --> 00:26:05,710
Displaying to everyone that Messi was the greatest of all time,

196
00:26:05,710 --> 00:26:10,049
heading into the 2013-2014 season,

197
00:26:10,049 --> 00:26:14,670
Barcelona seemed to be heavily reliant on Lionel Messi to win games and trophies.

198
00:26:14,670 --> 00:26:17,789
Barcelona is arguably the greatest club side of all time,

199
00:26:17,789 --> 00:26:21,769
and that alone would be daunting enough until you factor in this man.

200
00:26:21,769 --> 00:26:25,170
The incomparable, the maestro, the unmarkable,

201
00:26:25,170 --> 00:26:29,109
Lionel Messi is simply the puzzle that Chelsea have to solve.

202
00:26:29,109 --> 00:26:31,250
Statistics and history go out of the window.

203
00:26:31,250 --> 00:26:34,849
The way he's playing is solely about us performing in these two games

204
00:26:34,849 --> 00:26:38,809
to try and stop him, and with the ability he's got, we have to be our best.

205
00:26:38,809 --> 00:26:42,549
Pundits were labelling the side's era as Messi-dependent.

206
00:26:42,549 --> 00:26:46,890
However, going into the 2014-2015 season,

207
00:26:46,890 --> 00:26:48,910
under the new management of Luis Enrique,

208
00:26:48,910 --> 00:26:52,849
new faces appeared within the Barcelona squad.

209
00:26:52,849 --> 00:26:56,569
These new faces would be Neymar and Luis Suarez,

210
00:26:56,569 --> 00:27:00,430
and together they were the incredible strike force known as MSN,

211
00:27:00,430 --> 00:27:06,029
and were terrifying in front of goal.

212
00:27:06,029 --> 00:27:10,369
Always throughout time, there's been forward lines that have excited people

213
00:27:10,369 --> 00:27:15,869
and gone down in legend, and Barcelona obviously had one of those

214
00:27:15,869 --> 00:27:20,670
in the MSN combination, Messi, Suarez, Neymar,

215
00:27:20,670 --> 00:27:26,150
which came a few years after Real Madrid's BBC with Bale, Benzema and Cristiano.

216
00:27:26,150 --> 00:27:28,849
It was a wonderful, wonderful set-up.

217
00:27:28,849 --> 00:27:32,529
Neymar, Suarez and Messi in the same side.

218
00:27:32,529 --> 00:27:36,049
Messi with his incredible goal-scoring attributes,

219
00:27:36,049 --> 00:27:41,690
but also the wonderful assists that he brings to the side and to the other two.

220
00:27:41,690 --> 00:27:44,829
Suarez, absolutely deadly in front of goal,

221
00:27:44,829 --> 00:27:47,029
a finisher supreme.

222
00:27:47,029 --> 00:27:52,329
And Neymar, the kind of maverick on the other side, unpredictable,

223
00:27:52,329 --> 00:27:56,549
can be performing at a level below the other two quite often,

224
00:27:56,549 --> 00:27:59,650
but can also on his day be absolutely sensational.

225
00:27:59,650 --> 00:28:04,690
And who would not want to be part of that front line?

226
00:28:04,690 --> 00:28:09,670
Together, they scored a staggering 270 goals in just the one season.

227
00:28:09,670 --> 00:28:11,670
They also helped assist each other,

228
00:28:11,670 --> 00:28:15,650
achieving a total of 133 assists between them.

229
00:28:15,650 --> 00:28:18,910
They also went on to win back-to-back La Liga titles,

230
00:28:18,910 --> 00:28:21,769
two Spanish Cups, a Spanish Super Cup,

231
00:28:21,769 --> 00:28:24,509
a Champions League, a European Super Cup

232
00:28:24,509 --> 00:28:26,529
and a FIFA Club World Cup,

233
00:28:26,529 --> 00:28:30,430
totaling eight incredible trophies in just two seasons.

234
00:28:30,430 --> 00:28:36,769
I always said that I don't play to be the best in history,

235
00:28:36,769 --> 00:28:39,289
or the best of the moment, or anything like that.

236
00:28:39,289 --> 00:28:42,450
I play to try to do things right,

237
00:28:42,450 --> 00:28:49,170
first for the team, whether it's Barcelona or the Argentine national team,

238
00:28:49,170 --> 00:28:52,529
then for the people and, above all, for myself.

239
00:28:52,529 --> 00:28:57,549
It makes me feel good when things go my way,

240
00:28:57,549 --> 00:28:59,049
and that's how I live.

241
00:28:59,049 --> 00:29:03,869
That's why I'm not afraid of what people say.

242
00:29:03,869 --> 00:29:06,410
I'm beyond all that, for the good, for the bad.

243
00:29:06,410 --> 00:29:10,170
With Messi, Suárez and Neymar at the wheel,

244
00:29:10,170 --> 00:29:13,210
Barcelona were achieving record-breaking seasons.

245
00:29:13,210 --> 00:29:15,529
It seemed like the dependency on Messi was gone

246
00:29:15,529 --> 00:29:33,809
and they could all work together to win as many league titles as possible.

247
00:29:33,809 --> 00:29:37,329
Playing in the World Cup is different to everything else.

248
00:29:37,329 --> 00:29:40,089
To be able to play in the World Cup is something very nice.

249
00:29:40,089 --> 00:29:43,089
I think the best teams are there,

250
00:29:43,089 --> 00:29:46,710
and it's going to be very difficult for everyone.

251
00:29:46,710 --> 00:29:49,769
I hope things go well for Argentina,

252
00:29:49,769 --> 00:29:52,690
and that we can achieve our objective.

253
00:29:52,690 --> 00:29:53,789
We're going to enjoy it.

254
00:29:53,789 --> 00:29:57,150
It's in South America, and we're going to be close to our fans.

255
00:29:57,150 --> 00:29:59,650
I'm sure it's going to be great.

